    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP is leaning heavily into favorable pitching matchups today to close the gap in R and RBI. **Mickey Moniak** leads the charge with an elite 75.97 score; the combination of a high-ceiling matchup against Sasaki (5.52 xERA) and the benefit of a premium #2 spot in the order makes him our most potent asset. **Max Muncy** (71.26) and **Corbin Carroll** (71.32) are the pillars of the lineup, with **Max Muncy** capitalizing on a massive 19% SP skill advantage against Schultz, while **Corbin Carroll** remains a must-start despite facing a tougher Gausman, as his elite speed and xwOBA efficiency keep his floor safely in the high-70s. We are also monitoring the #1 slot for **James Wood**; his 66.68 score is driven by the volume of plate appearances at the top of the order, even against a decent arm in Ray.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench involved **Alex Freeland**, who posted a respectable 52.07 but ultimately couldn't crack the threshold to displace the high-floor production of **Jose Caballero**. While **Jose Caballero** struggles with a negative SP skill offset against the dangerous Ragans, his 13% dynamic platoon edge against the southpaw provides the necessary utility to keep him in the starting nine over **Alex Freeland**, whose value is currently stifled by a #9 batting order assignment. Meanwhile, **Austin Riley** remains a volatile asset; his 55.10 score is contingent on confirmed lineup placement, and with a pending status, we are wary of the 1.86s pop-time risk from the opposing catcher dampening his SB upside. Finally, **Tyler Soderstrom** serves as a strong leverage play; his 66.21 score is significantly bolstered by a 19% SP skill bump, making him an excellent bet against the subpar Schultz.",
